intermediate_en_text:
The Prime Minister of Zanzibar, Mr Khamis Omar, has been elected as the new chairman of the African Union Commission.

Mr Omar was elected by the AU member states during the 29th AU summit in Addis Ababa, Ethiopia, on Sunday. He will be the first head of the AU Commission from Africa's Eastern region.

He will replace South Africa's Nkosazana Dlamini-Zuma, who is ending her second term after eight years at the helm of the AU.

Mr Omar, a former foreign minister, will serve for a five-year term.

The new AU chairman said he would focus on improving the union's performance and building peace and security in Africa.

He said he would also work towards ensuring that the AU plays a leading role in global affairs.

The AU is made up of 55 member states. It was established in 2002 to promote unity and development in Africa.

It has its headquarters in Ethiopia's capital, Addis Ababa.

Mr Omar was born in 1964 and studied law at the University of Dar es Salaam. He worked as a lawyer before entering politics.

He became a member of parliament in 2000 and served as foreign minister between 2005 and 2010.

Mr Omar was elected as the president of Zanzibar in 2010 and re-elected in 2015. He is a member of the ruling CCM party.

The AU has been criticised for being ineffective and slow in responding to crises in Africa.'Instructions:
